<paragraph blockId="45.[151,1437,764,2015]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,276,764,791]" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Both sexes of this species can be differentiated from others of the genus by the combination of two submarginal cells, pronotal lobe black (
<figureCitation box="[608,702,801,827]" captionStart="FIGURES 99–105" captionStartId="47.[151,264,1911,1936]" captionTargetBox="[163,1425,193,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@47.[163,1425,166,1891]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="FIGURES 99–105. Liphanthus ancashensis sp. nov., paratype male. 99: lateral habitus, 100: face, frontal view, 101: T7, dorsal view of cleared tergum, to show pygidial plate, 102: S6 oblique ventral view of cleared sternum, to show process (red arrow); 103: S7, 104: S8, 105: genital capsule. Scale bars Fig. 99 1mm, Figs. 100–101 0.5mm, Figs. 102–105 0.25mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3345489/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Figs. 99</figureCitation>
&amp; 
<figureCitation box="[744,789,801,828]" captionStart="FIGURES 106–108" captionStartId="48.[151,264,1617,1642]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,166,1597]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[151,1435,166,1597]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURES 106–108. Liphanthus ancashensis sp. nov., allotype female: 106: lateral habitus, 107: face, frontal view, 108: metatibial apex to show curved metatibial spurs. Scale bars Figs. 106–107 1mm, Fig. 108 0.5mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3345491/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">106</figureCitation>
), metatibial spurs curved (
<figureCitation box="[1098,1199,801,827]" captionStart="FIGURES 106–108" captionStartId="48.[151,264,1617,1642]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,166,1597]" captionTargetId="figure@48.[151,1435,166,1597]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="FIGURES 106–108. Liphanthus ancashensis sp. nov., allotype female: 106: lateral habitus, 107: face, frontal view, 108: metatibial apex to show curved metatibial spurs. Scale bars Figs. 106–107 1mm, Fig. 108 0.5mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3345491/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 108</figureCitation>
). Other species with two submarginal cells and curved metatibial spurs have a yellow pronotal lobe. The males are unique among all 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Sharifi &amp; Graham &amp; Packer" authorityYear="2019" box="[151,277,873,899]" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Liphanthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="46" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[151,277,873,899]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Liphanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with two submarginal cells in having a mostly reddish metasoma and among all species of the genus in having a posteroventrally oriented process on S6 (
<figureCitation box="[722,822,909,935]" captionStart="FIGURES 99–105" captionStartId="47.[151,264,1911,1936]" captionTargetBox="[163,1425,193,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@47.[163,1425,166,1891]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="FIGURES 99–105. Liphanthus ancashensis sp. nov., paratype male. 99: lateral habitus, 100: face, frontal view, 101: T7, dorsal view of cleared tergum, to show pygidial plate, 102: S6 oblique ventral view of cleared sternum, to show process (red arrow); 103: S7, 104: S8, 105: genital capsule. Scale bars Fig. 99 1mm, Figs. 100–101 0.5mm, Figs. 102–105 0.25mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3345489/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 102</figureCitation>
). The hidden sterna are also unique: S7 has the apical lobes reduced to a pair of minute angulations (
<figureCitation box="[672,768,945,971]" captionStart="FIGURES 99–105" captionStartId="47.[151,264,1911,1936]" captionTargetBox="[163,1425,193,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@47.[163,1425,166,1891]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="FIGURES 99–105. Liphanthus ancashensis sp. nov., paratype male. 99: lateral habitus, 100: face, frontal view, 101: T7, dorsal view of cleared tergum, to show pygidial plate, 102: S6 oblique ventral view of cleared sternum, to show process (red arrow); 103: S7, 104: S8, 105: genital capsule. Scale bars Fig. 99 1mm, Figs. 100–101 0.5mm, Figs. 102–105 0.25mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3345489/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 103</figureCitation>
) and S8 has the anterior margin immediately in front of the anterior margin of the lateral lobes (
<figureCitation box="[554,652,981,1007]" captionStart="FIGURES 99–105" captionStartId="47.[151,264,1911,1936]" captionTargetBox="[163,1425,193,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@47.[163,1425,166,1891]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="FIGURES 99–105. Liphanthus ancashensis sp. nov., paratype male. 99: lateral habitus, 100: face, frontal view, 101: T7, dorsal view of cleared tergum, to show pygidial plate, 102: S6 oblique ventral view of cleared sternum, to show process (red arrow); 103: S7, 104: S8, 105: genital capsule. Scale bars Fig. 99 1mm, Figs. 100–101 0.5mm, Figs. 102–105 0.25mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3345489/files/figure.png" pageId="45" pageNumber="46">Fig. 104</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
